Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had been growing ever larger in the face of falling home prices.
Now that the government is fully backing Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to cover everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Do the venerable principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to bear the consequences of their errors?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Primarily, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Zudem wurden die von Fannie und Freddie ausgegebenen Anleihen weithin so angesehen, als wären sie mit einer stillschweigenden Garantie der US-Regierung ausgestattet.
Obwohl es keine offizielle Garantie gab, könnte das Ausbleiben einer Rettungsaktion seitens der US-Regierung das Vertrauen in Staatspapiere und – weil sie mit diesen in Verbindung gebracht werden – auch in andere Finanztitel untergraben.
Die Probleme reichen weit über die US-Wirtschaft hinaus.
Die Weltwirtschaft wurde in den letzten Jahren durch bemerkenswerte spekulative Höhenflüge und Abstürze von Anlagewerten angetrieben, was Fragen des Vertrauens, aber auch der Fairness in die Gleichung einbringt.
Auch in vielen anderen Ländern gehen derzeit ähnliche Höhenflüge des Häusersektors zu Ende, und sie stehen möglicherweise vor denselben Qualen – und denselben moralischen Dilemmata –, die die US-Wirtschaft derzeit durchlebt.
And the problem is not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are also involved.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar booms and busts in stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they continued, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could seize the global economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, aid fails to arrive.
People's reactions to these events depend on their emotions and their sense of justice.
The described booms and busts have caused a large redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the housing market did well or badly depending on their timing.
People will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what was told to them and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets in which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
Politics can only react generally and cannot treat each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times in many countries was spectacular.
But were the capital investments sold at too high a price in their respective markets?
Did cynical sellers here and elsewhere lead people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
Surely, it is certain that although there may have been a lot of "cheap chatter" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not starving.
Yet we cannot casually conclude from this that all their losses should be left untouched.
The nagging problem is one of "faith and trust."
National economies flourish only when "faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative booms have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments did so against faith and trust.
Take the investors who purchased Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the US government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of crisis, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
Government officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of discovering capitalism and its power to transform, reshape national economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and faith.
A treatment perceived as unfair can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose trust in businesses and therefore are less willing to make their valuable capital and labor available to them.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
